    "In this case, even if the attacker passes steps 2-6 of Algorithm II, the request message must be signed with the private key of the third-party entity in order to pass steps 7-11.",
    "However, the private key of a third-party entity is kept private only for that individual.Suppose an attacker is included in the system as a patient.Patients do not have authority over or access to other patients' EMRs.",
    "Patients can only authorize or deauthorize third-party entities for their own EMRs.",
    "The inclusion of an attacker in the system as a patient does not pose a security problem for the EMRs of other patients.1: Decrypt encrypted fragments by using symmetric encryption keys and merge the fragments 2: for i ← 0, count(encrpyted f ragments) do Delete previous patient EMR fragments 12: for i ← 0, count(fragments) do 13: create the new symmetric key -→ newSecretKey i 14:encrypt the f ragment i by using the newSecretKey i 15:encrpyted f ragmenti = f ragment (i)newSecretKeyi 16:save the encrpyted f ragmenti to distiributed database 17:add the new addresses of encrpyted f ragmenti and newSecretKey i to the storage list18: encrypt the storage list by using the p id privateKey 19: encrpytedStorageList p id = storagelist p id privateKey 20: end for 21: Save blok id, p id, Hash(EM R p id), timestamp, encrpytedStorageList p id, diseaseDescription p id, previous block hash to the blockchain as a new block 22: end ifIn this study, a new scheme is proposed for the secure storage and fast sharing of patient EMRs.",
    "In the proposed scheme, a document-oriented database is used to store data, and a blockchain is used for access control."
